n3. Swap t02 <-> c01: gate producing t02 now outputs c01, gate producing c01 now outputs t02\n4. Swap z04 <-> b03: gate producing z04 now outputs b03, gate producing b03 now outputs z04\n\nList all gates after swaps:\n```\nx00 XOR y00 -> z00\nx00 AND y00 -> c00\nx01 XOR y01 -> t01\nt01 XOR c00 -> a01      (swap 1: was z01)\nx01 AND y01 -> z01      (swap 1: was a01)\nt01 AND c00 -> b01\nz01 OR b01  -> t02       (swap 3: was c01)\nx02 XOR y02 -> c01       (swap 3: was t02)\nc01 XOR t02 -> z02       (note: this gate uses c01 and t02 as inputs - but c01 is now from XOR(x02,y02) and t02 is from OR(z01,b01))\nx02 AND y02 -> a02\nc01 AND t02 -> z03       (swap 2: was b02)\na02 OR z03  -> c02       (a02 OR b02 -> c02, but b02 is now z03... wait no, the inputs reference wire NAMES)\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. The key question: when my detection algorithm processes this bit-by-bit, starting from bit 0 with carry=\"c00\", at bit 1 it would:\n1. Find XOR(x01, y01) -> t01. ti = \"t01\".\n2. Find XOR(t01, c00) -> ? It outputs \"a01\". So xorTC outputs \"a01\" not \"z01\".  \n3. Since xorTC.out !== \"z01\", it does doSwap(\"a01\", \"z01\") — correctly detects swap 1.\n4. After doSwap, the gates are now corrected for that swap.\n5. AND(x01, y01) -> a01 (corrected back). ai = \"a01\"\n6. AND(t01, c00) -> b01. bi = \"b01\"\n7. OR(a01, b01) -> ? Now what's the output?\n\nAfter doSwap at step 3, the original gate that had `out: \"z01\"` (which was AND(x01,y01)) gets its output set to \"a01\", and the gate that had `out: \"a01\"` (which was XOR(t01,c00)) gets its output set to \"z01\". Good.\n\nBut swap 3 also happened: the original OR gate (a01 OR b01 -> c01) had its output swapped to t02 (swap 3). So after swap 3, OR(a01, b01) -> t02 (where a01 was further swapped with z01 by swap 1). \n\nAfter the detection corrects swap 1, we have:\n- XOR(t01, c00) -> z01 (corrected)\n- AND(x01, y01) -> a01 (corrected)\n- OR(a01, b01) -> t02 (still swapped from swap 3)\n\nWait but the OR gate's inputs reference wire names \"z01\" and \"b01\" because swap 1 changed the AND gate's output from a01 to z01... no wait. In the test's swapOutputs function, it only swaps the .out field. The .in1 and .in2 fields of other gates are NOT changed. So after all test swaps:\n\nGate: `a01 OR b01 -> c01` becomes (after swap 3) `a01 OR b01 -> t02`. The inputs are still `a01` and `b01`.\n\nBut the wire named `a01` is now produced by `t01 XOR c00 -> a01` (due to swap 1). \n\nAfter the algorithm's doSwap(\"a01\", \"z01\"), the algorithm changes the gate outputs back:\n- `t01 XOR c00 -> z01` (was a01, now corrected)\n- `x01 AND y01 -> a01` (was z01, now corrected)\n\nBut `a01 OR b01 -> t02` still has `.in1 = \"a01\"` — which now points to AND(x01,y01)'s output. Hmm but also, in the algorithm, findGate searches for OR gate with inputs ai=\"a01\" and bi=\"b01\". It finds the gate `a01 OR b01 -> t02` because its inputs match. But the output is t02 not c01.\n\nSo at step 7, the algorithm finds OR(a01, b01) -> t02. carry = \"t02\".\n\nNow on to bit 2:\n- xi = \"x02\", yi = \"y02\", zi = \"z02\"\n- Find XOR(x02, y02): this gate outputs \"c01\" (due to swap 3). So ti = \"c01\".\n- Find XOR(c01, t02): looking for XOR with inputs \"c01\" and \"t02\". The original gate is `c01 XOR t02 -> z02` (originally `t02 XOR c01 -> z02`, with the test swaps making t02->c01 and c01->t02 as outputs). Wait, but the gate's inputs are the original wire names...\n\nI realize I need to think about this differently. The gates' input wire names are NEVER changed. Only the output wire names are swapped. So the gate that was originally:\n```\nt02 XOR c01 -> z02\n```\nStill has in1=\"t02\", in2=\"c01\", out=\"z02\" — none of those were the outputs that got swapped. So it's unchanged.\n\nBut now, wire \"t02\" is produced by OR(a01, b01) (due to swap 3), and wire \"c01\" is produced by XOR(x02, y02) (due to swap 3). So functionally this gate takes the carry from bit 1 (which is correct since t02 = carry from